      <hedline>
        <hl1>Alzheimer's Victims</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel G Fish letter on Jonathan Kozol's Aug 22 article scores New York City for aggressively suing spouses for cost of nursing home care for Alzheimer's disease victims provided under Medicaid</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Losing My Father, One Day at a Time,'' by Jonathan Kozol (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Losing My Father, One Day at a Time,'' by Jonathan Kozol (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
        <p>The financial situation for couples, when one is in a nursing home under Medicaid, is actually worse than Mr. Kozol describes. Not only must the spouse who remains at home endure the ''sadness of Alzheimer's'' and ''mandatory destitution,'' now she must also endure the threat of being sued by New York City. New York, which runs the Medicaid program, is now aggressively suing spouses for the cost of care that it has provided.</p>
        <p>The typical case is a woman in her late 70's who cares for her husband at home by herself for five years, until her own health is compromised. Reluctantly, she accepts nursing-home placement for her husband and Medicaid. Living alone, she dreads the knock of the process server at her door.</p>
        <p>It is time for the city to cease bringing such suits.</p>
        <p>DANIEL G. FISH  New York, Aug. 23, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a former president of the National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys.</p>
      </block>
